"1322":"1322","1355":"1355","Aft 1387":"after 1387","1375":"1375","1397":"1397","1350":"1350","1409":"1409","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Wall, Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Wall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Wall, Lichfield, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Swinfen and Packington, Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Packington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Haddon Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Haddon Hall, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Swynfen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Swinfen (Staffs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Swiffen","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Swinfen   with loss of /n/ before a fricative consonant."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Swynfen was born about 1350, in Packington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Swynfen, was 29 and his mother, Helena, was 26. He married Joan de Pipe after 1387. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1409, in Wall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60, and was buried in Wall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1350–1409":"umbes 1350–1409","1350–1409":"1350–1409","1355–1411":"1355–1411","1397–1425":"1397–1425","1322–1375":"1322–1375","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","Abt 1350":"umbes 1350","1425":"1425","1325":"1325","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1322":"1322","1355":"1355","Aft 1387":"pärast 1387","1375":"1375","1397":"1397","1350":"1350","1409":"1409","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wall, Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Wall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wall, Lichfield, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swinfen and Packington, Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Packington, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Haddon Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Haddon Hall, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1350–1409":"noin 1350–1409","1350–1409":"1350–1409","1355–1411":"1355–1411","1397–1425":"1397–1425","1322–1375":"1322–1375","1325–Female":"13